Tutorial 2 - Exploring Typescript

10 steps

In this tutorial, explore Typescript and validate your code by introducing types and type-safety. Identify similarities and differences between Javascript and Typescript. Lastly, rewrite Javascript equivalents of your code from Quest 1 to Typescript and learn why type-safety is a good developer experience for web development.

For technical help on the StackUp platform & quest-related questions, join our Discord, head to the | quest-help-forum channel and look for the correct thread to ask your question.

Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

Finished Quest 1

Learning Outcomes

You will be able to:

  • Learn basic Typescript
  • Apply its type system more effectively when transforming Javascript code
  • Explain why developers should use Typescript

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 10

  • Step 1: What is Typescript?

    Head to the official Typescript website. You can read in the earlier parts of the page the description about Typescript.

    It even has the "What is Typescript?" section. As described, it's a superset of Javascript with the added syntax for types which improves developer experience. It also uses type inference to easily reason while you write your code.

    According to the 2020 Developer Survey conducted by Stack Overflow, Typescript is the 2nd most loved programming language. Typescript continues to be the admired and desired language on the 2024 Developer Survey conducted by Stack Overflow, getting a score of about 70%.

    Why Use Typescript?

    Typescript reduces bugs introduced to codebases by avoiding the pitfalls of Javascript's type system as Javascript is a weakly-typed programming language. Not sanitising input to the intended data type is cumbersome with Javascript. With Typescript, it avoids such pitfalls, allowing developers to "Describe the shape of objects and functions" in their code.

    A Very Simplistic Explanation of How Typescript Works

    Since Typescript is a superset of Javascript, this means that most Javascript code is valid code on Typescript. However, you have to take note that Typescript transpiles into Javascript code (other documentation will tell you the term "compiles to Javascript").

    What this means, a software tool called a transpiler (or compiler) will transform Typescript code, usually by first doing validation checks such as data types being consistently used in the code before stripping them off to become valid Javascript code.

    There is a part in the Soar with Deno that mentions why terminologies such as "transpiler" and "compiler" are interchangeable. To quote:

    Transpiling is transforming one language into another i.e. Typescript to Javascript. This is different from a similar process called compiling when code is transformed into machine code which is readily fed through the CPU or any processing unit. The two are used interchangeably a lot but it's good to know the differences first.

    In Deno, Typescript Compiler (TSC), Speedy Web Compiler (SWC) and other similar tools, are transpilers. But for now, let's just use the term compiler to avoid confusion with their documentation.

    The most probably reason why it is called still called a compiler was the analogy between Javascript and assembly. You can think of Javascript as the "assembly of the web". Thus, it actually makes sense to also call it a compiler instead of a transpiler.

    Web3 and Typescript

    Web3 (aka Web 3.0), as part of the world wide web, also contains multiple Javascript libraries and tools such as ethers.js and web3.js.

    With the introduction of Typescript, libraries such as viem.sh and wagmi.sh allows developers to build Ethereum apps with a type-safe language. It also allows increased maintainability while also delivering a great developer experience.

    More and more Javascript libraries are slowly shifting towards adding Typescript variants, increasing the adoption of the language and maintainability of popular libraries and tooling.

    ---------

    In the following steps in the tutorial, you will be rewriting or modifying some Javascript code to their close Typescript equivalents. Head to the root directory of your project. Create a directory called typescript. The typescript directory is where you will create the files for each code example you come across in the following steps

  • Step 2: Variables in Typescript

    You will be using the same project used in Quest 1, if you have not started with Quest 1, please head back and follow all steps from Quest 1.

    At the root directory of your project, create a new directory called typescript if you have not already. Head to the typescript directory and create a new file called variables.ts. Remember that you also have created a javascript directory with the file variables.js from Quest 1? Let's repeat that step but instead, you will do it here. Write the following code to variables.ts.

    // Variables in Javascript

let foo1 = "Hi";

{
  var foo2 = "Hello";
  let foo1 = "Goodbye!";
  const foo3 = "I am only here"
  let foo4 = "I am only here as well"
}

// But foo3 and foo4 cannot be called here.
console.log(foo1, foo2, foo3, foo4)
    TypeScript

    Now, run the following command at the root directory of your project.

    deno run typescript/variables.ts

    The command should give you an error similar to the screenshot below.

    Typescript also follows the same scoping and namespace rules as Javascript so do remember that some things you learned about variables in Javascript may also apply for Typescript. By now, you already know how to fix this issue. Fix the issues and try running the same command again.

    A quick check, your file explorer by now should look like this. If yours do not look like this, you might have skipped Quest 1. Please go back to Quest 1 and follow each step.

  • Step 3: Data Types in Typescript

    Javascript is a dynamically typed and weakly typed language. It's a dynamic language since variables can be assigned or reassigned with values of all types. In contrast, Typescript is a statically typed and strongly typed language.

    This is because Typescript was designed to fix the obscure and confusing type system of Javascript. Let's observe the behaviour when running the code from Quest 1 in Javascript.

    At the root directory of your project, head to the typescript directory and create a new file called data-types.ts. Write the following code to your new file data-types.ts. This is the same code you have from Quest 1.

    let variable = "foo";  // this is a string
variable = 0;  // variable is reassigned as a number
variable = false;  // variable is reassigned as a boolean
    TypeScript

    The previous code is valid Typescript. Like Javascript, the variables already know that the values are their data types. However, this is a violation because if you hover over the red squiggly underlines you see on your code from your Deno LSP, you will get a similar message similar to the screenshot below.

    You can actually run the command at the root directory of your project and see that there will be no error.

    deno run typescript/data-types.ts

    However, that defeats the purpose of using Typescript! In order to strictly enforce Typescript rules, add the --check flag for the Deno command like so.

    deno run --check typescript/data-types.ts

    This should give you a long error message like the screenshot below.

    By following or reading the error message, the fix is actually removing those reassignments and just assigning a string value for the variable. Replace all the previous code with the following snippet.

    let variable = "foo";  // this is a string

let foo = variable + 12;
foo = foo + " this is twelve and ";
foo = foo + 0;
console.log(foo);
    TypeScript

    This should only leave you with one warning from the LSP which you can ignore for now. Now you can try running the same command and it will not throw a compiler error.

    Remember the following code below from Quest 1?

    function addATrueNumber(x, y) {
  if ((typeof x === "number") && (typeof y === "number")) {
    return x + y;
  }
  throw new Error("One of the inputs is not a number", {
    cause: "Not a number.",
  });
}

const aTrueNumber = addATrueNumber(12, 12);
console.log(aTrueNumber);
    JavaScript

    Append this code and you should get an error message "TS7006 [ERROR]: Parameter 'y' implicitly has an 'any' type." after running the command again.

    Typescript discourages the use of any type which literally means "any kind of data type". It needs to be explicit and stated what input data types you have for your parameters, be it a function or a custom data type.

    This removes the usage of typeof, reducing the code into a more clear and saner code like the code snippet below.

    let variable = "foo";  // this is a string

let foo = variable + 12;
foo = foo + " this is twelve and ";
foo = foo + 0;
console.log(foo);

function addATrueNumber(x: number, y: number) {
	return x + y;
}

const aTrueNumber = addATrueNumber(12, 12);
console.log(aTrueNumber);
    TypeScript

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project.

    deno run --check typescript/data-types.ts

    Try experimenting by changing the parameter values on the variable aTrueNumber, specifically the function for where it gets its value e.g. from 12 to "12".

    Share your experience and what you think about Typescript's static typing over Javascript's dynamic typing in our Discord forum channel.

  • Step 4: Data Structures in Typescript

    Both Javascript and Typescript have primitive data structures called objects. An object is a mutable value. Most of the concepts you have learnt from Javascript on data structures also apply for Typescript.

    At the root directory of your project, head to the typescript directory and create a new file called data-structures.ts. Write the following code snippet to data-structures.ts.

    const x = [1, 2]; // an array
const y = {
  key: "pair",
  date: new Date(),
  generateDate() {
    this.date = new Date();
  },
}; // a key-value pair or a dictionary or object

console.log(x, typeof x);
console.log(y, typeof y);
y.generateDate();
console.log(y);
    TypeScript

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project to observe its behaviour.

    deno run --check ./typescript/data-structures.ts

    Both Javascript and Typescript allow developers to manipulate objects around such as extending or wrapping an existing object wrapper or even create custom objects. So the same code snippet, for example, from Quest 1 is still valid Typescript.

    let person = {};
person.age = 20;
person.name = {};
person.name.first = "John";
person.name.last = "River";
person.name.updateFirstName = function (x) {
  this.first = x;
};
console.log(person);
person.name.updateFirstName("Jonathan");
console.log(person);
    TypeScript

    However, as always, the linter coming from the LSP will complain e.g. the property age does not exist on type {}. You can check this by running the same command again on the terminal at the root directory of your project.

    deno run --check ./typescript/data-structures.ts

    To solve this, you must define the "shape" of the data structure e.g. the property fields and their corresponding data type.

    For example, consider the following code snippet where you will use the type keyword to create your custom type for a data structure that is equivalent to the data structure you created for the person variable.

    type Person = {
	age: number,
	name: {
		first: string,
		last: string,
		updateFirstName: Function
	}
}

let person: Person = {
  age: 20,
  name: {
    first: "John",
    last: "River",
    updateFirstName: function (x: string) {
		this.first = x
	}
  }
}
console.log(person);
person.name.updateFirstName("Jonathan");
console.log(person);
    TypeScript

    Or declare them already so the type inference will do the work for you if you don't want to create a custom data type.

    let person = {
  age: 20,
  name: {
    first: "John",
    last: "River",
    updateFirstName: function (x: string) {
		this.first = x
	}
  }
}
console.log(person);
person.name.updateFirstName("Jonathan");
console.log(person);
console.log(typeof person)
    TypeScript

    Another approach is using OOP using classes to define objects. For example, you can replace the same code with the following code.

    class Person {
	public age: number;
	public name: {
		first: string;
		last: string;
		updateFirstName: Function
	}
	constructor(age: number, firstName: string, lastName: string) {
		this.age = age;
		this.name = {
			first: firstName,
			last: lastName,
			updateFirstName: (x: string) => {
				this.name.first = x
			}
		}
	}
}

let person = new Person(20, "John", "River");
console.log(person);
person.name.updateFirstName("Jonathan");
console.log(person);
console.log(typeof person)
    TypeScript

    As you might have noticed, there might be some advantages and disadvantages between writing a custom type and custom class object.

    One clear advantage between the two is that a developer can check the actual object if they are an instance of a certain class object with the instanceof keyword.

    console.log(person instanceof Person)
    TypeScript

    You cannot do this if you only write the type (or interface which will be discussed in Quest 3).

  • Step 5: Conditionals in Typescript

    At the root directory of your project, head to the typescript directory and create a new file called conditionals.ts.

    Write the following code snippet to conditionals.ts.

    const veryTrue = true;
const veryFalse = false;

if (veryTrue) {
  console.log("Very True");
}

if (!veryFalse) {
  console.log("Very False");
}
    TypeScript

    It should not be any different than the code from Quest 1. Append the following code snippet to conditionals.ts.

    function divide(x, y) {
  if (y === 0) {
    throw new Error(
      `Division by zero. Tried to operate ${x} with divisor ${y}.`,
      { cause: "Division by zero." },
    );
  }
  return x / y;
}

try {
  const quotient1 = divide(100, 10);
  const quotient2 = divide(10, 0);
  console.log(quotient1, quotient2);
} catch (err) {
  if (err instanceof Error) {
    console.error(err.message);
  } else {
    console.error(`Unknown error ${err}.`);
  }
}
    TypeScript

    Guess what happens after running the following command below at the root directory of your project.

    deno run --check typescript/conditionals.ts

    It will throw an error that the parameters for the divide function should not be an implicit type of any. To resolve this, just add the desired data types for the parameter for the divide function. The following code snippet is the updated version of the divide function.

    function divide(x: number, y: number) {
	if (y === 0) {
	  throw new Error(
		`Division by zero. Tried to operate ${x} with divisor ${y}.`,
		{ cause: "Division by zero." },
	  );
	}
	return x / y;
  }
    TypeScript
  • Step 6: Loops in Typescript

    Loops in Javascript are also valid in Typescript. At the root directory of your project, head to the typescript and create a file called loops.ts.

    By this time, you will notice that this section will repeat the same things from Quest 1. Let's do this!

    Loops are quite useful for iterating over a collection of data, usually data inside of arrays. It is also useful for running n times of the same block of code.

    For example, a classic for loop is pretty useful for repetitive execution at a specific number of times. Head to the typescript directory and create a new file called loops.ts. Write the following code to loops.ts.

    const MAX = 10;
for (let i = 0; i < MAX; i++) {
	console.log(i);
}
    TypeScript

    Here, you have set three statements within the () parentheses. The first is the initialization statement, where it is executed once e.g. to initialize and define a counter variable i. The second is the predicate or condition similar to how you write an if-else block statement; this is evaluated before each iteration. The third statement is what's executed after each iteration e.g. to modify the counter variable.

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project to observe its behaviour.

    deno run --check ./typescript/loops.ts

    You can also do the same thing with a while loop. Append and write the following code.

    let d = 0;
while (d < MAX) {
	console.log(d);
	d++;
}
    TypeScript

    You can see a similarity between if-else block statement and the while loop. But in a while loop, the code inside the block will execute as long as the predicate holds true i.e. d < MAX.

    You can also write this with a do-while loop. Append and write the following code.

    d = 0;
do {
  console.log(d);
  d++;
} while (d < MAX);
    TypeScript

    All three loops are valid and quite useful when iterating over values such as array indices or running the same code n times where n is a number.

    In another example, users tend to use the classic for loop to iterate over an array similar to the code below.

    const arr = [1, 2, 3];
for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
  console.log(i, arr[i]);
}
    TypeScript

    Fortunately, there is a better way and that is by using the for-in loop. The syntax is cleaner and easier to understand. It's useful to iterate over the properties (keys) of an object. You can replace the previous for loop with the following code.

    
for (const key in arr) {
  console.log(key, arr[key]);
}
    TypeScript

    You can also just use the for-of loop variant when you want to just iterate over the values.

    for (const val of arr) {
  console.log(val);
}
    TypeScript

    Lastly, collections such as arrays and strings have a forEach method that you can use if you prefer the functional programming syntax. Here is what it should look like when using the same variable arr with forEach. 

    arr.forEach((x) => console.log(x));
    TypeScript

    This might not be considered a loop since it's a method, but it's quite useful if you prefer using this over a loop.

    Loops can use the continue and break keywords to continue and break loop iteration. For example, the following code below shows how to use the two keywords.

    for (const val of arr) {
  if (val >= 2) {
    console.log("Break here");
    break;
  }
}

const arr2 = [25, 100, 50, 150];

for (const val of arr2) {
  if (val === 100) {
    console.log("Continue if 100");
    continue;
  } else if (val === 50) {
    console.log("Break if 50");
    break;
  }
}
    TypeScript

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project to observe its behaviour.

    deno run --check ./typescript/loops.ts

    The only issue is that you cannot use the continue and break keywords to manipulate the iteration bound by the forEach method. Fortunately, loops inside the forEach method can still use the continue and break keywords. For example, consider the following code below.

    const arr3 = [10, 15, 2, 12, 26];
arr3.forEach((x) => {
  console.log(`Max iterations for i variable to cover: ${x}`);
  for (let i = 0; i < x; i++) {
    const i2 = i * 2;
    if (i2 > 5) {
      console.log("Break here!");
      console.log(`Value of i before break: ${i}`);
      break;
    } else if ((i % 2) === 0) {
      console.log("Continuing here!");
      continue;
    }
  }
});
    TypeScript

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project to observe its behaviour.

    deno run --check ./typescript/loops.ts

    The full code for loops.ts is shown below.

    const MAX = 10;
for (let i = 0; i < MAX; i++) {
  console.log(i);
}

let d = 0;
while (d < MAX) {
  console.log(d);
  d++;
}

d = 0;
do {
  console.log(d);
  d++;
} while (d < MAX);

const arr = [1, 2, 3];
for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
  console.log(i, arr[i]);
}

for (const key in arr) {
  console.log(key, arr[key]);
}

for (const val of arr) {
  console.log(val);
}

arr.forEach((x) => console.log(x));

for (const val of arr) {
  if (val >= 2) {
    console.log("Break here");
    break;
  }
}

const arr2 = [25, 100, 50, 150];

for (const val of arr2) {
  if (val === 100) {
    console.log("Continue if 100");
    continue;
  } else if (val === 50) {
    console.log("Break if 50");
    break;
  }
}

const arr3 = [10, 15, 2, 12, 26];
arr3.forEach((x) => {
  console.log(`Max iterations for i variable to cover: ${x}`);
  for (let i = 0; i < x; i++) {
    const i2 = i * 2;
    if (i2 > 5) {
      console.log("Break here!");
      console.log(`Value of i before break: ${i}`);
      break;
    } else if ((i % 2) === 0) {
      console.log("Continuing here!");
      continue;
    }
  }
});
    TypeScript
  • Step 7: Promises in Typescript

    Promises in Javascript are also valid Typescript. Head to the typescript directory and create a new file called promises.ts.

    Write the following code to promises.ts. You have to remember that the code below comes from ./javascript/promises.js.

    let promise = new Promise(function (resolve, reject) {
  let success = true; // Change this to false to test the rejection

  if (success) {
    resolve("Operation was successful!");
  } else {
    reject("Operation failed.");
  }
});

console.log(await promise);

/*
 * Handrolled version of setTimeOut.
 */
const customSetTimeOut = (x) =>
	new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
	  if ((typeof x) !== "number") {
		const errorVal = new Error("Not a number", {
		  cause: "Value is not a number.",
		});
		return reject({
		  errorVal,
		  value: x,
		});
	  } else {
		const currentTime = new Date();
		const previousSeconds = currentTime.getTime();
		const fullFilledSeconds = previousSeconds + (x * 1000);
  
		let newTime = new Date();
		do {
		  newTime = new Date();
		} while (newTime.getTime() < fullFilledSeconds + 1);
		return resolve(`Finished the ${x} seconds countdown!`);
	  }
	});
  
  customSetTimeOut("2 ").then((x) => console.log(x)).catch((err) => {
	console.error(err);
	console.log("Attempting to convert string to a number value!");
	// If it's not a number, set the timeout to 0. This just serves as an example.
	const number = !isNaN(err.value.trim())
	  ? Number.parseInt(err.value.trim())
	  : 0;
	customSetTimeOut(number); // we will not handle the error here for now
	console.log(`Conversion successful. Timeout lasted in ${number} seconds`);
  });
    TypeScript

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project.

    deno run --check typescript/promises.ts

    You should get an error that you can't have an implicit type any for the parameter x.

    Now that you are using Typescript, you can remove some of the code since Typescript has static type checking. This will also resolve the issue of having implicit type any as well by just explicitly telling the parameter type.

    Change the customSetTimeOut function to the following code

    /*
 * Handrolled version of setTimeOut.
 */
const customSetTimeOut = (x: number) =>
	new Promise((resolve, reject) => {

		const currentTime = new Date();
		const previousSeconds = currentTime.getTime();
		const fullFilledSeconds = previousSeconds + (x * 1000);

		let newTime = new Date();
		do {
			newTime = new Date();
		} while (newTime.getTime() < fullFilledSeconds + 1);
		return resolve(`Finished the ${x} seconds countdown!`);

	});
    TypeScript

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project.

    deno run --check typescript/promises.ts

    This way, you can avoid putting in numbers that are actually strings in your code.

  • Step 8: Handling Multiple Promises in Typescript

    At the root directory of your project, head to the typescript directory. Create a new file called multiple-promises.ts.

    Write the following code to the new file.

    const arr = [];
for (let i = 2; i < 100; i+=2) {
  const promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    if ((i % 2) === 0) {
      return resolve(i + 2);
    }
    return reject(-100);
  });
  arr.push(promise);
}

console.log(arr);

for (const element of arr) {
  const val = await element;
  console.log(val);
}

for await (const element of arr) {
  console.log(element);
}

Promise.all(arr).then((values) => {
  values.forEach((value) => console.log("From Promise.all", value));
}).catch((err) => console.error(err));
    TypeScript

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project to observe its behaviour.

    deno run --check ./typescript/multiple-promises.ts

    The same concepts you have learned from Quest 1 still apply for the Typescript code used here.

  • Step 9: Object Oriented Programming In Typescript

    Typescript also supports OOP such as classes and inheritance.

    Head to the typescript directory and create a new file called oop.ts. Write the following code to oop.ts.

    class Animal {
  constructor(name) {
    if (name === undefined) return this.name = "Unknown";
    return this.name = name;
  }
}

const newAnimal = new Animal("Weird");
console.log(newAnimal);
    TypeScript

    Although this is still considered valid Javascript code, Typescript will complain for some violations. You can see this after you run the following command.

    deno run --check typescript/oop.ts

    Typescript is also very strict with the properties present in objects and classes. If it is not defined, then it's, therefore, not defined. So calling a non-existent property will cause the compiler to throw an error. To resolve this, ensure that you have defined the properties for your objects and classes.

    Because of this, rewrite and replace your old code to the following code below.

    class Animal {
	public name: string;

	constructor(name: string | undefined) {
		if (!name) {
			this.name = "Unknown"
		} else {
			this.name = name
		}
	}
}

const newAnimal = new Animal(undefined);
console.log(newAnimal);
    TypeScript

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project to observe its behaviour.

    deno run --check ./typescript/oop.ts

    Yours should never throw an error and show you a message.

    Inheritance is still similar. However, appending the following code will give you errors.

    class Mammal extends Animal {
  constructor(name, genus, species) {
    super(name);
    if (genus === undefined || species === undefined) {
      throw new Error("No species added.", { cause: "Invalid input." });
    } else {
      this.genus = genus;
      this.species = species;
    }
    this.classification = "Mammalia";
  }
  getSpecies() {
    console.log(`${this.genus} ${this.species}`);
  }
}

const human = new Mammal("Stackie", "Homo", "sapiens");
console.log(human.name);
human.getSpecies();
    TypeScript

    Replace the previous Mammal class definition with the following code.

    class Mammal extends Animal {
	public genus: string;
	public species: string;
	public classification: string;
	constructor(name: string, genus: string | undefined, species: string | undefined) {
	  super(name);
	  if (genus === undefined || species === undefined) {
		throw new Error("No species added.", { cause: "Invalid input." });
	  } else {
		this.genus = genus;
		this.species = species;
	  }
	  this.classification = "Mammalia";
	}
	getSpecies() {
	  console.log(`${this.genus} ${this.species}`);
	}
  }
    TypeScript

    To hide some properties, the syntax is still the same but you still have to explicitly define the data types. So class Reptile from Quest 1's example should be the following code.

    class Reptile extends Animal {
	private genus: string;
	public species: string;
	public classification: string;
	constructor(name: string, genus: string | undefined, species: string | undefined) {
	  super(name);
	  if (genus === undefined || species === undefined) {
		throw new Error("No species added.", { cause: "Invalid input." });
	  } else {
		this.genus = genus;
		this.species = species;
	  }
	  this.classification = "Reptilia";
	}
	getSpecies() {
	  console.log(`${this.genus} ${this.species}`);
	}
  }
  
  const crocodile = new Reptile("Angel", "Crocodylus", "novaeguineae");
  console.log(crocodile.genus); // this will error. experiment by removing this line.
  crocodile.getSpecies();
    TypeScript

    Note that # and private keywords label the property as private. But they cannot be used interchangeably despite similar usage.

    As you have noticed, the differences between Javascript and Typescript is that Typescript forces discipline into developers as they should always be explicit of how data is structured in their code rather than letting a language with a confusing and weak type system do its job.
